[DhtmlXQ_comment45]Mag:And red wins after black resigned.||Post-game conclusion: ||Because of this game, seldom does black play C2=5 for the 5th move any more.||In this game, red took control of the game early on and played the game with ferocity. During the midgame, red targeted black's congested palace center and with superb precision, offered five consecutive sacrifices to maneuver his chariots to the final position. Each move was like a dagger slicing through black's heart.||This is textbook material on how to attack black's centroid horse (yes, this is the official term by the WXF to describe the horse in the center of the palace).||Huang: In this opening, red defers movement of his chariot to play P7+1 first would push the game into complex variations. If black played the cross river chariot as in this game, red could choose to play the side elephant and then sacrifice his 3rd rank pawn. If black does not play R8+5 (move 4), red could play P3+1 for the double headed snake pawn formation.Red would then utilize the ranked chariots for an attack at his own pace.||Jim: For beginners, there is no way that black can resolve red's C5=6 checkmate.[/DhtmlXQ_comment45]
